<font color="#FF0000">IN THE REAR WITH THE GEAR</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug 16 11:08:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Chet,<br>
It would not have bothered me one bit to have served in the rear with the gear. <br>
Keenan, (never knew his first name) was captured during a fierce battle on operation Foster by the NVA. He played dead while the enemy stripped him of his gear, uniform and weapon. He continued to play dead while the battle ensued all around him for another six hours. He was later discovered by Foxtrot 2/7 that was Sparrowhawked in to get us out of a spot Charlie had already determined was his.  We had already circled the wagon, fixed bayonets and handed out gas masks. The reward Keenan received was a job in the rear as our new mail clerk. How we envied him but none of us would have wanted to do or to go through what he had. I do not think I would have been able to. His presence of mind told him to let go of the weapon when the gooks yanked it from his hand. I would have resisted and would have been killed. Remember the primary training of a Marine is that he and his weapon are inseparable. Keenan is alive today. Should he feel guilty for having given up his weapon? For having been assigned to the rear? To me he was and remains a real hero, he is alive today, with a family of his own. <br><br>
I served on the Los Angeles Police Department for 22 years only because of the pay and benefits. Often I heard the sound of AK47's in the middle of the night while on patrol in Watts, Southeast LA or the 77th street area. It didn't send an adrenaline rush through me, it was more like a nauseating, sick sense of hopelessness, of sucking chest wounds, splintered bones, much pain and helplessness. Just another night in the city, another eight hour watch, blow out the candle and hit the sack, tomorrow Charlie will poke out his head and if you're lucky you catch him in the act and book him for his crimes. But you know in your mind (that is in conflict with your heart) that the system will let him out by daybreak and the following night you will do the same. Nothing gained, nothing solved animals will be animals. The river rat (like those that opposed our efforts in Nam) will come out at night and sometimes the rat would trip a trip flare and you would catch a glimpse of him and open up with a full 20 round clip. Click the claymore and toss a few grenades where you saw the shadow move and if you were real lucky hit him once or twice. But, if you did his dead carcass would stay out in the wire and the following night another praying animal would come out to take a bite and nibble on the remains and trip another flare and the next day you would request more ammo from the rear and Keenan would make sure that we got our mail, even the draft notices and mail from nagging wives who asked you to write about anything but what was real.<br><br>
All that has been there in the back of my mind but that has never been my life, that has never been my memories until I chose to revisit them. It wasn't until a little over a year ago that I began to reconsider what had happened in Nam from the diary I kept there and it was then I sought out those memories. Even so, they are not part of my life as I exist today and once this book is finished, I will move on having said my peace.<br>
I have dozens and dozens of short stories to tell and I crave to do so. I have books to write on the early 1st century and can't wait to do so, but that diary and the Vietnam experience was there in the back of my mind and I knew that I had a story to tell and that it needed to be told and that has consumed a greater part of my spare time these past few months but once its finished so will that chapter in my life. I will visit the wall once again and drop a copy dedicated to Ronald Allan Moore at the base of where his name is inscribed on that black mirrored wall and make peace with the world having done what I know I must do, then I will move on to my passion and love and do what I desire to accomplish with my life. <br><br>
Chet, I'm glad you started this thread, during our San Antonio reunion a GySgt that served with H&amp;S came up and asked if I would be interested in some slides he had taken during the time he served in the rear with 3/7. Yesterday I received them in the mail. Among the slides are six great photos of Foxtrot 2/7 as they loaded on board choppers to come bail us out of that spot in the rivers bend. <br>
Thank you Gunny, thank you Chet.<br>

